WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:04.680
Welcome to the Learn Linux
in 5 Days course.

2
00:00:04.680 --> 00:00:08.830
On day one you'll learn what Linux is,
how it came to be and

3
00:00:08.830 --> 00:00:11.750
some of its strengths and weaknesses.

4
00:00:11.750 --> 00:00:16.155
You'll also learn a few different methods
to gaining access to an already installed

5
00:00:16.155 --> 00:00:18.070
and running Linux system.

6
00:00:18.070 --> 00:00:21.850
If you want to learn how to install
Linux on your own, don't worry,

7
00:00:21.850 --> 00:00:23.860
you'll learn how to do that too.

8
00:00:23.860 --> 00:00:27.890
Finally, on day one, we'll talk about the
various ways to connect to a Linux system

9
00:00:27.890 --> 00:00:30.650
and the software you'll need to do so.

10
00:00:30.650 --> 00:00:34.345
You'll start out day two by learning
about the Linux directory structure and

11
00:00:34.345 --> 00:00:37.875
where various components of
the operating system reside.

12
00:00:37.875 --> 00:00:41.205
Next, you'll get an introduction to
the Linux command line interface, and

13
00:00:41.205 --> 00:00:44.815
learn some of the most essential and
often used commands.

14
00:00:44.815 --> 00:00:48.355
Even the most experienced Linux users
need help from time to time, and

15
00:00:48.355 --> 00:00:50.615
you'll learn how and
where to find that as well.

16
00:00:52.070 --> 00:00:55.730
You'll also learn about the superuser
account, why it exists and

17
00:00:55.730 --> 00:00:57.410
when you need to use it.

18
00:00:57.410 --> 00:01:00.210
You'll wrap up day two by learning
some directory shortcuts and

19
00:01:00.210 --> 00:01:02.892
how to navigate about the file system.

20
00:01:02.892 --> 00:01:06.525
Day three will include lessons on file and
directory permissions.

21
00:01:06.525 --> 00:01:11.115
You'll learn how to read permissions,
what they mean, and how to set them.

22
00:01:11.115 --> 00:01:13.785
You'll also pick up some tips
on working with groups and

23
00:01:13.785 --> 00:01:15.855
the permissions you
should use when doing so.

24
00:01:16.975 --> 00:01:20.025
Next, you'll learn two commands
that will help you find any file or

25
00:01:20.025 --> 00:01:22.335
directory on a Linux system.

26
00:01:22.335 --> 00:01:25.485
You'll learn how to view the contents
of files and how to edit them.

27
00:01:26.600 --> 00:01:28.700
We'll also cover command-line editors,

28
00:01:28.700 --> 00:01:31.540
as well as editors that you can
use in a graphical environment.

29
00:01:32.850 --> 00:01:37.280
You'll start out day four by learning
how to delete, copy, move, and

30
00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:39.880
rename files and directories.

31
00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:42.510
You'll tackle input and
output redirection before

32
00:01:42.510 --> 00:01:46.080
learning how to compare the contents
of files and directories.

33
00:01:46.080 --> 00:01:49.300
Next, I'll show you how to search for
data within files.

34
00:01:49.300 --> 00:01:52.990
You'll learn how to customize your command
line shell prompt to your liking and

35
00:01:52.990 --> 00:01:55.440
learn how to use aliases.

36
00:01:55.440 --> 00:01:58.560
Finally, on day four, you'll learn
how to transfer data between your

37
00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:01.450
local operating system and a Linux host.

38
00:02:01.450 --> 00:02:04.600
You'll even learn how to copy files
from one Linux system to another.

39
00:02:06.070 --> 00:02:11.170
On the final day you'll learn how to
examine and manipulate processes and jobs.

40
00:02:11.170 --> 00:02:15.300
You'll learn how to automate tasks and
make them recurring events.

41
00:02:15.300 --> 00:02:19.410
We'll talk about how to switch
between users on a Linux system too.

42
00:02:19.410 --> 00:02:22.620
You'll also pick up some tips that will
greatly speed up your work flow at

43
00:02:22.620 --> 00:02:24.260
the command line.

44
00:02:24.260 --> 00:02:29.080
Finally, you'll wrap up the course with
learning how to find, install, update, and

45
00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:29.900
remove software.

